recordings.rmk: I filtered some of the wind noise and deleted distracting loud crow vocalizations because the sound I was capturing is very high pitched.  The target was in a Live Oak tree (Quercus virginiana) which contains a regular nesting hole for this species.  I am presuming, without any specific knowledge otherwise, that this is a fledgling exchanging vocalizations with an adult bird.  Alternately it might be an exchange between two birds in courtship.  If anyone has more exact knowledge I would appreciate it.

recordings.loc: Horseshoe Pond, Merrimack, Hillsborough County, New Hampshire
recordings.rmk: Atypical vocalization, "towhee-like" to me. Heard on multiple occasions at this location but I finally saw the bird this time. Habitat is open water with marsh and scrub-shrub, with some red maple swamp, bordering upland forest and suburban residential area. While the bird had been heard in the marsh before, this time it was at about eye level on a pine branch in a backyard. The identity of the bird had been a mystery for some time. I have not heard this particular vocalization at any other location, nor do any existing titmouse recordings here match it precisely, so I hope this can help document it and help anyone else who may have heard something similar!

recordings.rmk: Having trouble identifying this high-pitched, two-note call (song?). Recorded in a cypress swamp in SE Virginia.  My impression was that it was coming from the  middle of the understory, but I couldn't be sure. It was very difficult to determine location.  Thought maybe Brown Creeper, but I can't find an example of a two-note call (or song) on XC. Also heard Black-and-White Warbler in the same location, but that didn't seem to match up on XC either. Also tried Carolina Chickadee.
